<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>Mthandeni Shangase of the Dagga Party of South Africa said: “We’re tired of beings arrested for smoking traditional medicine. “Dagga was used by our forefathers so why are we being arrested for following in their footsteps?” Shangase said it wasn’t fair that drunkards walked freely in public and were not treated as criminals.“The municipality has to find a way to address this matter with the higher structures of government,” he said.Sandile Jangase (38), a non-smoker, said he joined the march to support the smokers.“ I live with people who use dagga and they don’t trouble anyone.” When the SunTeam arrived outside the municipal offices, cops were monitoring the situation.Deputy mayor Nokulunga Blose told marchers she wouldn’t accept their memorandum because the municipality had nothing to do with their grievances. “You came to the wrong place. You should have gone to the department of justice.”